(5. Wing length)

106
00:04:15,205 --> 00:04:16,635
It's 183.5mm.

107
00:04:17,245 --> 00:04:19,505
- It's 183.5mm.
- It's 183.5mm.

108
00:04:19,975 --> 00:04:23,445
(All five measurements have been completed.)

109
00:04:25,985 --> 00:04:27,084
What's in there?

110
00:04:27,085 --> 00:04:28,884
- This is called a PIT tag.
- Okay.

111
00:04:28,885 --> 00:04:31,854
By injecting this into the penguin, we can track it...

112
00:04:31,855 --> 00:04:33,285
- and distinguish each individual.
- Each individual?

113
00:04:33,385 --> 00:04:37,424
We have a long device shaped like Excalibur.

114
00:04:37,425 --> 00:04:39,395
When you scan with it, it shows a number.

115
00:04:40,295 --> 00:04:41,295
(Injection begins.)

116
00:04:41,296 --> 00:04:42,334
It would hurt.

117
00:04:42,335 --> 00:04:45,365
(He's too into it.)

118
00:04:48,175 --> 00:04:49,374
(Flapping)

119
00:04:49,375 --> 00:04:50,675
It hurts.

120
00:04:51,945 --> 00:04:52,974
(He's flapping as well.)

121
00:04:52,975 --> 00:04:56,015
It would hurt. It's okay. It'll just sting a little.

122
00:04:57,585 --> 00:05:00,244
You don't say something like this. "It'll just sting a little."

123
00:05:00,245 --> 00:05:01,985
They say this to people.

124
00:05:02,185 --> 00:05:03,885
Instead, I thoroughly rub the skin.

125
00:05:04,125 --> 00:05:07,755
Now, we're done with one penguin.

126
00:05:08,555 --> 00:05:10,824
You need to do everything by hand,

127
00:05:10,825 --> 00:05:12,725
- so it takes a long time.
- Right.

128
00:05:13,065 --> 00:05:14,764
It'd be hard to measure many penguins in a day.

129
00:05:14,765 --> 00:05:16,565
- In a day...
- Ten?

130
00:05:16,665 --> 00:05:18,905
- Ten in one day is...
- It's a lot, right?

131
00:05:19,105 --> 00:05:20,535
It's really a lot.

132
00:05:20,635 --> 00:05:22,975
You did it a bit faster with us,

133
00:05:23,235 --> 00:05:24,304
but with just the three of you, it won't be as quick.

134
00:05:24,305 --> 00:05:26,975
(Measuring penguins takes more effort than one might think.)

135
00:05:27,415 --> 00:05:30,685
(How is the other team attaching the tracking devices?)

136
00:05:30,815 --> 00:05:32,045
- Shall we begin?
- Yes.

137
00:05:32,385 --> 00:05:34,114
- Soo Hyang, do you have a notebook?
- Yes.

138
00:05:34,115 --> 00:05:36,685
Number three. Prepare the tape.

139
00:05:37,325 --> 00:05:38,524
It pooped.

140
00:05:38,525 --> 00:05:40,185
(It shot its droppings.)

141
00:05:40,555 --> 00:05:41,894
(Research always begins with poop.)

142
00:05:41,895 --> 00:05:43,095
I already got poop on my clothes.

143
00:05:44,125 --> 00:05:46,895
Penguins poop a lot.

144
00:05:47,635 --> 00:05:49,435
- Prepare the tape.
- Okay.

145
00:05:49,995 --> 00:05:53,164
Could I have four 12cm strips of tape?

146
00:05:53,165 --> 00:05:54,175
Sure.

147
00:05:55,575 --> 00:05:58,675
(Jong Won prepares the tape.)

148
00:06:02,645 --> 00:06:05,285
(His hand is shaking.)

149
00:06:06,645 --> 00:06:10,354
(He's struggling with super-strong waterproof tape.)

150
00:06:10,355 --> 00:06:12,354
- It's hard to tear it, isn't it?
- It is.

151
00:06:12,355 --> 00:06:14,825
The adhesive is strong,

152
00:06:15,555 --> 00:06:16,895
so it's difficult to tear it off.

153
00:06:19,795 --> 00:06:22,435
(The tracking device will be attached here.)

154
00:06:23,765 --> 00:06:28,605
(She carefully secures it with waterproof tape.)

155
00:06:29,805 --> 00:06:31,574
Prepare the GPS.

156
00:06:31,575 --> 00:06:33,005
- Okay.
- GPS.

157
00:06:33,575 --> 00:06:36,514
The GPS number is 00.

158
00:06:36,515 --> 00:06:38,515
(She secures the tracking device with waterproof tape.)

159
00:06:39,245 --> 00:06:43,315
(Date, the number assigned to the penguin)

160
00:06:43,515 --> 00:06:46,525
- Prepare the dye.
- Okay.

161
00:06:47,925 --> 00:06:50,965
(While Soo Hyang is preparing the dye, )

162
00:06:51,795 --> 00:06:53,264
(Jong Won is observing something.)

163
00:06:53,265 --> 00:06:54,865
(Staring)

164
00:06:55,135 --> 00:06:58,435
Is the penguin carrying stones to the nest a male?

165
00:06:59,005 --> 00:07:00,304
Both males and females do it.

166
00:07:00,305 --> 00:07:02,075
They're a nice couple.

167
00:07:03,035 --> 00:07:05,245
They're probably a couple,

168
00:07:05,705 --> 00:07:07,445
but they might be cheating.

169
00:07:09,575 --> 00:07:11,645
- Penguins cheat too?
- Yes.

170
00:07:12,445 --> 00:07:15,915
(Sometimes, if a penguin isn't satisfied with its mate...)

171
00:07:16,815 --> 00:07:18,484
(Honey, where are you going?)

172
00:07:18,485 --> 00:07:20,325
(Oh, my gosh!)

173
00:07:20,895 --> 00:07:24,064
(Penguins have affairs too.)

174
00:07:24,065 --> 00:07:26,165
They have affairs just like humans.

175
00:07:29,495 --> 00:07:31,334
- Here it is.
- Thank you.

176
00:07:31,335 --> 00:07:32,435
- Should we flip the penguin?
- Yes.

177
00:07:33,975 --> 00:07:36,004
I'm sorry.

178
00:07:36,005 --> 00:07:37,005
(They're careful not to hurt it.)

179
00:07:37,405 --> 00:07:38,844
Oh, my.

180
00:07:38,845 --> 00:07:40,944
(A number is marked on its white belly.)

181
00:07:40,945 --> 00:07:42,115
You wrote three.

182
00:07:42,215 --> 00:07:45,044
- Yes. Number 3.
- Number 3.

183
00:07:45,045 --> 00:07:47,114
With an extra line.

184
00:07:47,115 --> 00:07:49,315
Because its mate has been given number three.

185
00:07:49,415 --> 00:07:51,155
It means it's the mate of number three.

186
00:07:52,685 --> 00:07:54,154
(Numbers are marked on the penguin's body with dye...)

187
00:07:54,155 --> 00:07:55,724
(so that it can be quickly identified...)

188
00:07:55,725 --> 00:07:57,055
(when changing the devices.)

189
00:07:57,225 --> 00:08:00,064
Soo Hyang, shall we go and put the egg back in the nest?

190
00:08:00,065 --> 00:08:01,065
Yes.

191
00:08:01,735 --> 00:08:04,565
(Give my egg back to me right now!)

192
00:08:05,205 --> 00:08:06,534
It's angry.

193
00:08:06,535 --> 00:08:07,675
(I'm sorry. Please wait a little.)

194
00:08:08,275 --> 00:08:12,045
(She returns the egg first.)

195
00:08:13,805 --> 00:08:15,975
This is number 3. That's number 13.

196
00:08:17,885 --> 00:08:21,315
(She releases the penguin by the nest.)

197
00:08:21,515 --> 00:08:24,455
(Figuring out where it is first)

198
00:08:25,325 --> 00:08:27,125
- Can they find the nest?
- Yes, they know where it is.

199
00:08:29,895 --> 00:08:32,465
- Amazing.
- It's interesting.

200
00:08:32,865 --> 00:08:34,764
They don't know sometimes,

201
00:08:34,765 --> 00:08:38,135
but most of them find their nest right away.

202
00:08:38,865 --> 00:08:40,605
Won't the penguins try to remove the tracker?

203
00:08:41,235 --> 00:08:43,205
We should change it every five days.

204
00:08:43,305 --> 00:08:44,404
They won't try to get it off,

205
00:08:44,405 --> 00:08:46,245
but they might lose it while swimming.

206
00:08:48,515 --> 00:08:49,515
Are we doing it together?

207
00:08:49,516 --> 00:08:51,144
(They can't study the Antarctic ecosystem...)

208
00:08:51,145 --> 00:08:52,615
(without the help of penguins.)

209
00:08:53,645 --> 00:08:57,014
This task takes a lot of effort.

210
00:08:57,015 --> 00:09:01,025
Right. It would be very difficult to do it alone.

211
00:09:01,855 --> 00:09:05,165
The penguin research team went through a lot.

212
00:09:05,695 --> 00:09:10,195
They were literally working among the penguins.

213
00:09:10,905 --> 00:09:14,135
With the high altitude, the wind blew fiercely.

214
00:09:14,875 --> 00:09:17,844
When I briefly took off my gloves, my hands froze,

215
00:09:17,845 --> 00:09:19,145
making writing difficult.

216
00:09:19,705 --> 00:09:21,645
Watching them continue their research...

217
00:09:22,015 --> 00:09:25,715
despite being hungry,

218
00:09:26,085 --> 00:09:27,415
I felt a mix of sympathy...

219
00:09:27,815 --> 00:09:32,325
and admiration for them.

220
00:09:32,755 --> 00:09:36,455
They wouldn't be able to do this job without a sense of purpose.

221
00:09:37,925 --> 00:09:42,035
I was reminded once more...

222
00:09:42,595 --> 00:09:43,735
of the importance and significance...

223
00:09:44,505 --> 00:09:46,634
of penguin research for humanity.

224
00:09:46,635 --> 00:09:47,635
(He realized how important penguin research is.)

225
00:09:48,005 --> 00:09:53,275
(Once again, they get closer to Antarctica through experience.)

226
00:09:55,045 --> 00:09:59,285
(Another day has passed at King Sejong Station.)

227
00:09:59,685 --> 00:10:00,714
(Chef of Antarctica)

228
00:10:00,715 --> 00:10:05,085
(It's already the 4th day since they arrived in Antarctica.)

229
00:10:11,195 --> 00:10:15,365
(The crew members are busy getting ready to move in the morning.)

230
00:10:19,105 --> 00:10:20,334
Hello.

231
00:10:20,335 --> 00:10:23,505
(The crew members of Antarctica get on the boat.)

232
00:10:23,905 --> 00:10:26,175
(As everyone waves them off, )

233
00:10:26,275 --> 00:10:27,644
Bye.

234
00:10:27,645 --> 00:10:30,174
(where are they going?)

235
00:10:30,175 --> 00:10:31,715
See you later.

236
00:10:32,915 --> 00:10:37,285
This is Kwon Oh Seok and 12 others, leaving for the Argentine Base.

237
00:10:37,925 --> 00:10:40,455
(Argentine Base?)

238
00:10:41,395 --> 00:10:42,395
(Why are they going to the Argentine Base?)

239
00:10:42,396 --> 00:10:44,925
The weather is nice today.

240
00:10:45,465 --> 00:10:48,195
- Hello.
- Hello.

241
00:10:48,865 --> 00:10:52,365
Thank you for adapting so well to the harsh conditions in Antarctica.

242
00:10:52,935 --> 00:10:54,035
We should thank you.

243
00:10:54,505 --> 00:10:57,174
I want to brief you...

244
00:10:57,175 --> 00:10:58,845
on the tasks you'll be performing today.

245
00:10:58,945 --> 00:11:03,114
Each country carefully inspects its supplies...

246
00:11:03,115 --> 00:11:04,915
- and ships plenty, - Okay.

247
00:11:05,645 --> 00:11:08,414
but there's always a shortage in Antarctica.

248
00:11:08,415 --> 00:11:11,284
Especially when it comes to food,

249
00:11:11,285 --> 00:11:14,354
some items are plentiful while others are scarce,

250
00:11:14,355 --> 00:11:17,724
so we exchange what's abundant...

251
00:11:17,725 --> 00:11:19,724
and what's lacking...

252
00:11:19,725 --> 00:11:20,794
among ourselves.

253
00:11:20,795 --> 00:11:21,835
Does the Korean base borrow a lot of food?

254
00:11:22,035 --> 00:11:24,905
Yes. For example, lamb...

255
00:11:25,005 --> 00:11:28,105
- isn't commonly used in Korea.
- Right.

256
00:11:28,205 --> 00:11:30,534
But South American bases have it in abundance,

257
00:11:30,535 --> 00:11:33,444
so they share it or exchange it for something else.

258
00:11:33,445 --> 00:11:38,084
That can only happen among brothers.

259
00:11:38,085 --> 00:11:40,484
In Antarctica, no matter how powerful a country is,

260
00:11:40,485 --> 00:11:45,384
it's not enough to survive on its own.

261
00:11:45,385 --> 00:11:46,784
